collections.name: Beautiful Art By PacoGuillem
collections.description:
Paco Guillem is a Valencian photographer with a distinguished career spanning over four decades. His work focuses on transforming everyday objects and industrial waste into striking photographic art, raising awareness about recycling and environmental protection. His minimalist and thought-provoking style has been showcased in prominent venues such as the Cultural Houses of Dénia and Catarroja, the Baleària Foundation, and the International Biennial of Épinal in France.

Highlights of his career include designing iconic promotional posters, including those for the Valencia Popular Marathon in 1986 and 1987, as well as creating the official logo for its 20th anniversary. Paco's work has earned him a nomination for the 2024 Photography Award from the Amedeo Modigliani Foundation in Rome.

Currently, his photography explores themes of sustainability and beauty in discarded objects, with a significant upcoming exhibition at the Mutua Levante Foundation in Alcoy in May 2025. Paco Guillem's

collections.name: BUSY by James Merrill
collections.description:
Art Blocks Collection: Curated

Project Description: _BUSY_ is a generative reflection of urban complexity and interconnected systems.

As an artist who works at the intersection of code and mechanical plotting, James Merrill has become fascinated with the contrast between overwhelming city dynamics and the quiet stillness of his Vermont studio. He seeks to transform apparent chaos into structured beauty, creating works that reveal the hidden patterns within our seemingly disordered world.

Merrill says, "What drew me to generative art was the ability to make programs that generate infinite numbers of outputs. I often observe cities as layered systems that we've normalized through familiarity, and I wonder how to capture that totality. I'm interested in offering viewers a god's eye perspective—not just of urban environments, but of the underlying coexisting elements that form them." This tension between randomness and order drives Merrill's creative process and shapes the intricate compositions that emerge.
BUSY explores the overwhelming sensation of being pulled in countless directions—notifications, movement, tasks—while seeking the underlying structure beneath.The work emphasizes relationships over randomness, causality over noise, and cause and effect over disorder. Drawing inspiration from highly detailed Wimmelbilder scenes, BUSY applies generative techniques to build complex compositions that feel both familiar and abstract.

This collection of 50 unique works invites viewers to discover new details with each viewing—much like exploring a metropolis where chaos resolves into structured complexity when viewed through the right lens.

collections.name: Entrenamiento
collections.description:
Art is the ethereal dance of my soul, a tapestry woven from threads of reality and imagination, each stroke a tender whisper echoing my innermost vision of the world. With a palette as vast as the cosmos, I employ plastic, corporeal, linguistic, and sonorous resources, sculpting ideas, emotions, perceptions, and sensations into existence.

For over four decades, my muse has been the beautiful game of football, a passion that has coursed through my veins since youth. From the pinnacle of international competition to the realm of visual artistry, I have traversed the fields of expression with a ball at my feet, each touch a brushstroke upon the canvas of my existence.

Professional football, a symphony of individual brilliance and collective harmony, demands rigorous preparation of body, mind, and spirit. It is a collaborative endeavor, where the bonds forged amongst teammates elevate the sport to the realm of artistry.

collections.name: Faces of Alchemy: The Surreal Synthesis of Being
collections.description: Every day, we become new versions of ourselves—faces shaped by fleeting emotions, borrowed truths, and the quiet alchemy of existence. Faces of Alchemy captures this metamorphosis, where flesh fractures into filigree, blooms burst from bone, and circuits hum beneath skin. These surreal visages are not portraits but portals, reflecting the raw, imperfect beauty of our endless transformation—a reminder that to be human is to be forever in flux, sculpted by love, loss, and the weight of our own becoming.
